  <div class="hero">
    <h1>Widowmaker Heart Attack</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">The deadliest type of heart attack occurs when the Left Anterior Descending (LAD) artery — responsible for 40–50% of the heart's blood supply — becomes completely blocked.</p>
    <div class="warning">⚠️ If you suspect a heart attack, call 911 immediately. Every minute matters.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">🫀 The LAD Artery</h2>
    <div class="anatomy-box">
      <p style="color:#aaaacc; font-size:0.9rem; margin-bottom:1rem;">The heart has three major coronary arteries. A blockage in any can cause a heart attack — but the LAD supplies the most muscle.</p>
      <div class="artery-diagram">
        <div class="artery lad">
          <h4>Left Anterior Descending (LAD)</h4>
          <div class="pct">40–50%</div>
          <div class="label">of heart blood supply</div>
          <p>Feeds the left ventricle (main pumping chamber), septum, and apex. A complete blockage here = widowmaker.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="artery">
          <h4>Left Circumflex (LCx)</h4>
          <div class="pct" style="color:#aaaacc;">15–25%</div>
          <div class="label">of heart blood supply</div>
          <p>Wraps around the left side, feeding the lateral and posterior walls of the left ventricle.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="artery">
          <h4>Right Coronary (RCA)</h4>
          <div class="pct" style="color:#aaaacc;">25–35%</div>
          <div class="label">of heart blood supply</div>
          <p>Feeds the right ventricle, bottom of the left ventricle, and the electrical conduction system.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">📊 Key Statistics</h2>
    <div class="stats-grid">
      <div class="stat-card"><div class="value">~805K</div><div class="label">Heart attacks per year in the U.S.</div></div>
      <div class="stat-card"><div class="value">90–95%</div><div class="label">Survival with immediate PCI treatment</div></div>
      <div class="stat-card"><div class="value">30–50%</div><div class="label">Mortality without treatment</div></div>
      <div class="stat-card"><div class="value">90 min</div><div class="label">Critical window for PCI (door-to-balloon)</div></div>
      <div class="stat-card"><div class="value">40–50%</div><div class="label">Heart muscle supplied by the LAD</div></div>
      <div class="stat-card"><div class="value">2:1</div><div class="label">Male-to-female ratio under age 55</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">⚡ Risk Factor Assessment</h2>
    <p style="color:#8888aa; margin-bottom:1rem; font-size:0.9rem;">Select the option that best describes you for each factor. This is an educational estimate — not a medical diagnosis.</p>
    <div class="risk-box">
      <div id="riskForm"></div>
      <div class="risk-result" id="riskResult">
        <div class="score" id="riskScore"></div>
        <div class="level" id="riskLevel"></div>
        <div class="detail" id="riskDetail"></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">🚨 Warning Signs</h2>
    <div class="signs-grid">
      <div class="sign-card"><div class="icon">💔</div><h4>Severe Chest Pain</h4><p>Often described as an "elephant sitting on your chest." Intense pressure, squeezing, or tightness in the center or left side of the chest lasting more than a few minutes.</p></div>
      <div class="sign-card"><div class="icon">💪</div><h4>Radiating Pain</h4><p>Pain spreading from the chest to the left arm, jaw, neck, shoulder, or back. Can also radiate to both arms or the upper abdomen.</p></div>
      <div class="sign-card"><div class="icon">😰</div><h4>Cold Sweats</h4><p>Profuse sweating unrelated to physical activity or temperature. Often described as a "cold sweat" with clammy skin. A classic heart attack warning sign.</p></div>
      <div class="sign-card"><div class="icon">🫁</div><h4>Shortness of Breath</h4><p>Difficulty breathing that may occur with or without chest pain. Can feel like you can't get enough air, even at rest.</p></div>
      <div class="sign-card"><div class="icon">🤢</div><h4>Nausea & Vomiting</h4><p>Unexplained nausea, indigestion, or vomiting. More common in women and sometimes mistaken for food poisoning or acid reflux.</p></div>
      <div class="sign-card"><div class="icon">😵</div><h4>Lightheadedness</h4><p>Feeling faint, dizzy, or a sudden sense of impending doom. The body's response to reduced blood flow to the brain.</p></div>
    </div>

    <div class="guide" style="margin-top:1rem; border-color:rgba(224,90,90,0.3);">
      <h3>⚠️ Women May Experience Different Symptoms</h3>
      <p>Women are more likely to have atypical symptoms including unusual fatigue lasting days before the event, sleep disturbances, indigestion, anxiety, and back or jaw pain without chest pain. These subtler presentations lead to delayed diagnosis — one reason women have higher mortality rates from widowmaker heart attacks than men.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">⏱️ Critical Timeline</h2>
    <p style="color:#8888aa; margin-bottom:1rem; font-size:0.9rem;">From the moment the LAD becomes fully blocked, every minute counts. Here's what happens inside the heart — and what treatment looks like.</p>
    <div class="timeline">
      <div class="tl-item"><div class="time">0 minutes</div><h4>Complete LAD Blockage</h4><p>Blood flow to 40–50% of the heart muscle stops. Heart cells begin to be starved of oxygen. Symptoms typically begin immediately — crushing chest pain, sweating, shortness of breath.</p></div>
      <div class="tl-item"><div class="time">20–30 minutes</div><h4>Irreversible Damage Begins</h4><p>Heart muscle cells at the center of the affected zone begin to die. The damage spreads outward from the core. Cardiac arrest becomes increasingly likely.</p></div>
      <div class="tl-item"><div class="time">60–90 minutes</div><h4>Critical Treatment Window</h4><p>The "door-to-balloon" goal: a catheter with a tiny balloon is threaded to the blocked artery and inflated to restore blood flow (PCI/angioplasty). A stent is placed to keep it open. Best outcomes occur within this window.</p></div>
      <div class="tl-item"><div class="time">3–6 hours</div><h4>Extensive Damage Zone</h4><p>Without treatment, the dead zone expands significantly. The more muscle lost, the weaker the heart becomes permanently. Heart failure risk increases dramatically.</p></div>
      <div class="tl-item" style="opacity:0.8;"><div class="time">12+ hours</div><h4>Maximum Damage</h4><p>Nearly all at-risk heart muscle has been destroyed. Even with late intervention, the heart may be permanently weakened. Long-term complications are likely.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">🛡️ Prevention Strategies</h2>
    <div class="prevention-grid">
      <div class="prev-card"><h4>🚭 Stop Smoking</h4><p>Smoking doubles the risk of heart attack. Within 1 year of quitting, heart attack risk drops by 50%. Within 5 years, risk approaches that of a non-smoker.</p><span class="impact">↓ 50% risk in 1 year</span></div>
      <div class="prev-card"><h4>🏃 Exercise Regularly</h4><p>150+ minutes of moderate aerobic exercise per week. Even 30 minutes of brisk walking 5 days a week reduces cardiovascular risk significantly.</p><span class="impact">↓ 30–40% risk</span></div>
      <div class="prev-card"><h4>🥗 Heart-Healthy Diet</h4><p>Mediterranean or DASH diet: fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean protein, olive oil. Reduce sodium, processed meats, and trans fats.</p><span class="impact">↓ 25–30% risk</span></div>
      <div class="prev-card"><h4>💊 Manage Blood Pressure</h4><p>Target: below 120/80 mmHg. Uncontrolled hypertension is the #1 modifiable risk factor for heart attack. Medication + lifestyle changes work together.</p><span class="impact">↓ 20–25% risk per 10mmHg</span></div>
      <div class="prev-card"><h4>📊 Know Your Numbers</h4><p>Get a coronary calcium score (CAC) test after age 40. It detects plaque buildup in coronary arteries years before symptoms. Costs $75–200, no insurance needed.</p><span class="impact">Early detection</span></div>
      <div class="prev-card"><h4>⚖️ Maintain Healthy Weight</h4><p>BMI 18.5–24.9. Excess visceral fat (belly fat) increases inflammation and plaque formation in coronary arteries. Even losing 5–10% body weight helps.</p><span class="impact">↓ 3–5% risk per kg lost</span></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">❓ Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="faq">
      <details><summary>What is a widowmaker heart attack?</summary><div class="answer">A widowmaker heart attack occurs when the left anterior descending (LAD) artery — the largest artery supplying blood to the heart — becomes completely blocked. The LAD feeds blood to about 40–50% of the heart muscle, making a complete blockage life-threatening. The name comes from the historically high fatality rate, particularly among middle-aged men.</div></details>
      <details><summary>What is the survival rate of a widowmaker heart attack?</summary><div class="answer">The survival rate depends heavily on how quickly treatment is received. With immediate emergency care and PCI (percutaneous coronary intervention) within 90 minutes, survival rates are approximately 90–95%. Without treatment, the mortality rate is estimated at 30–50% within the first few hours. Overall hospital mortality for treated widowmaker heart attacks is approximately 5–8%.</div></details>
      <details><summary>What are the warning signs of a widowmaker heart attack?</summary><div class="answer">Warning signs include severe chest pain or pressure (often described as an elephant sitting on the chest), pain radiating to the left arm, jaw, neck, or back, profuse sweating, nausea or vomiting, shortness of breath, lightheadedness, and a sense of impending doom. Some patients, particularly women, may experience subtler symptoms like unusual fatigue, indigestion, or back pain in the days leading up to the event.</div></details>
      <details><summary>Can a widowmaker heart attack be prevented?</summary><div class="answer">While not all widowmaker heart attacks can be prevented, risk can be significantly reduced through lifestyle changes: not smoking, maintaining healthy blood pressure and cholesterol, regular exercise (150+ minutes per week), managing diabetes, maintaining a healthy weight, and managing stress. A coronary calcium score (CAC) test can detect early plaque buildup in the LAD artery before symptoms appear.</div></details>
      <details><summary>What is the LAD artery?</summary><div class="answer">The Left Anterior Descending (LAD) artery is the largest coronary artery. It branches from the left main coronary artery and runs along the front of the heart, supplying blood to approximately 40–50% of the heart muscle including the left ventricle (the heart's main pumping chamber), the interventricular septum, and the apex of the heart.</div></details>
    </div>

    <div class="disclaimer">
      <p><strong>Medical Disclaimer:</strong> This tool is for educational purposes only and is not a substitute for professional medical advice, diagnosis, or treatment. Always consult your physician or qualified healthcare provider with questions about a medical condition. If you think you are having a heart attack, call 911 immediately.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <script is:inline define:vars={{ riskFactors }}>
    const factors = riskFactors;
    const form = document.getElementById('riskForm');
    const selections = {};

    // Render form
    factors.forEach(f => {
      const div = document.createElement('div');
      div.className = 'risk-factor';
      div.innerHTML = `<label>${f.label}</label><div class="risk-options" data-factor="${f.id}">
        ${f.options.map((o, i) => `<div class="risk-opt" data-factor="${f.id}" data-idx="${i}" data-pts="${o.pts}">${o.text}</div>`).join('')}
      </div>`;
      form.appendChild(div);
    });

    // Handle clicks
    form.addEventListener('click', e => {
      const opt = e.target.closest('.risk-opt');
      if (!opt) return;
      const fid = opt.dataset.factor;
      const pts = parseInt(opt.dataset.pts);

      // Deselect others in same group
      document.querySelectorAll(`.risk-opt[data-factor="${fid}"]`).forEach(el => el.classList.remove('selected'));
      opt.classList.add('selected');
      selections[fid] = pts;

      // Calculate if all answered
      if (Object.keys(selections).length === factors.length) {
        showResult();
      }
    });

    function showResult() {
      const total = Object.values(selections).reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0);
      const maxScore = factors.reduce((a, f) => a + Math.max(...f.options.map(o => o.pts)), 0); // 22
      const pct = Math.round((total / maxScore) * 100);

      const result = document.getElementById('riskResult');
      const scoreEl = document.getElementById('riskScore');
      const levelEl = document.getElementById('riskLevel');
      const detailEl = document.getElementById('riskDetail');

      scoreEl.textContent = `${total}/${maxScore}`;

      result.className = 'risk-result visible';

      if (total <= 4) {
        result.classList.add('risk-low');
        levelEl.textContent = 'Low Risk Profile';
        detailEl.textContent = 'Your current risk factor profile suggests lower-than-average cardiovascular risk. Continue maintaining healthy habits. Consider a baseline coronary calcium score after age 40, and annual checkups with bloodwork.';
      } else if (total <= 9) {
        result.classList.add('risk-moderate');
        levelEl.textContent = 'Moderate Risk Profile';
        detailEl.textContent = 'You have some modifiable risk factors. Focus on the areas where you scored highest — these are your biggest opportunities for risk reduction. Discuss a coronary calcium score with your doctor, especially if you have family history.';
      } else if (total <= 15) {
        result.classList.add('risk-high');
        levelEl.textContent = 'Elevated Risk Profile';
        detailEl.textContent = 'Multiple risk factors are present. Strongly consider discussing a comprehensive cardiovascular assessment with your doctor, including a coronary calcium score and stress test. Aggressive lifestyle changes and possibly medication could significantly lower your risk.';
      } else {
        result.classList.add('risk-very-high');
        levelEl.textContent = 'High Risk Profile';
        detailEl.textContent = 'Your risk factor profile is significantly elevated. Please consult a cardiologist promptly for a full evaluation. Early intervention — including medication, lifestyle changes, and monitoring — can dramatically improve outcomes.';
      }

      result.scrollIntoView({ behavior: 'smooth', block: 'center' });
    }
  </script>
</SiteLayout>
